WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.796
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.404 --> 00:00:06.070
SPEAKER 1: Cool.

00:00:06.070 --> 00:00:07.070
Thank you so much.

00:00:07.070 --> 00:00:07.570
All right.

00:00:07.570 --> 00:00:10.290
I'm going to start with
a question for you all.

00:00:10.290 --> 00:00:11.746
Is anybody hungry?

00:00:11.746 --> 00:00:12.370
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:00:12.370 --> 00:00:12.730
SPEAKER 1: All right.

00:00:12.730 --> 00:00:13.600
Excellent.

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:15.940
So Chef [? DeeDee ?]
and her team

00:00:15.940 --> 00:00:20.050
are going to prepare some
great food for us after this.

00:00:20.050 --> 00:00:23.249
But you have to just bear
with me for a second.

00:00:23.249 --> 00:00:25.540
We're going to get to enjoy
these breakfast sandwiches.

00:00:25.540 --> 00:00:27.665
Pretty simple breakfast
sandwich-- cheese, sausage,

00:00:27.665 --> 00:00:28.165
eggs.

00:00:28.165 --> 00:00:29.950
But first, we've just
got to do something

00:00:29.950 --> 00:00:31.690
before you all get to eat this.

00:00:31.690 --> 00:00:32.189
Hold on.

00:00:32.189 --> 00:00:34.113
Just bear with me.

00:00:34.113 --> 00:00:34.738
[POURING WATER]

00:00:34.738 --> 00:00:35.692
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:42.860 --> 00:00:44.060
OK.

00:00:44.060 --> 00:00:45.057
We're getting ready.

00:00:45.057 --> 00:00:46.640
Now, you might be
wondering why I just

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:49.100
dumped an entire gallon of
water down the drain, why

00:00:49.100 --> 00:00:51.200
I would go and waste all
that water, especially

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:54.020
during Earth Week here on
Environment Day at Google,

00:00:54.020 --> 00:00:55.040
no less.

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:58.010
Well, to produce just the single
egg in this breakfast sandwich

00:00:58.010 --> 00:00:59.843
that we're going to
eat, we have to dump out

00:00:59.843 --> 00:01:01.799
not one but 53 gallons of water.

00:01:01.799 --> 00:01:04.340
That's how much water it takes
to produce just a single egg--

00:01:04.340 --> 00:01:06.260
53 gallons.

00:01:06.260 --> 00:01:08.540
To produce sausage,
that's another 500 gallons

00:01:08.540 --> 00:01:12.240
of water; and cheese, that's
another 50 gallons of water.

00:01:12.240 --> 00:01:15.680
That's what it takes to
produce protein from animals.

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:19.100
In the 15 years that I've
been researching food systems

00:01:19.100 --> 00:01:20.810
and advocating for
a better one, I've

00:01:20.810 --> 00:01:23.480
come to realize that the
number one most wasteful aspect

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:25.910
of our food system today
comes from the fact

00:01:25.910 --> 00:01:28.950
that we use animals
as a middleman.

00:01:28.950 --> 00:01:31.410
So here's what I mean--
first, we grow crops.

00:01:31.410 --> 00:01:33.170
We don't feeds those
crops to humans.

00:01:33.170 --> 00:01:35.780
First, we feed them to
animals to fatten them up.

00:01:35.780 --> 00:01:36.680
We raise the animals.

00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:37.971
We transport them to slaughter.

00:01:37.971 --> 00:01:40.299
And the rest is history.

00:01:40.299 --> 00:01:41.840
So animals are just
kind of middlemen

00:01:41.840 --> 00:01:44.060
between the crops we
produce to feed them

00:01:44.060 --> 00:01:47.570
and the protein they
produce to feed us.

00:01:47.570 --> 00:01:49.820
The problem is it's
super inefficient.

00:01:49.820 --> 00:01:51.860
Even in the best
cases, a farm animal

00:01:51.860 --> 00:01:54.530
converts only like
11% of what's called

00:01:54.530 --> 00:01:57.009
"feed energy" into human food.

00:01:57.009 --> 00:01:58.550
That means that
calorically speaking,

00:01:58.550 --> 00:02:02.510
89% percent of what we put
into an animal is wasted.

00:02:02.510 --> 00:02:05.570
And nearly all of these animals
in our food supply chain

00:02:05.570 --> 00:02:07.200
are chickens.

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:08.734
We're so knee-deep
in chickens today

00:02:08.734 --> 00:02:11.210
that every 60 seconds,
every single day,

00:02:11.210 --> 00:02:13.619
130,000 of these
animals are slaughtered.

00:02:13.619 --> 00:02:14.660
If you can imagine that--

00:02:14.660 --> 00:02:20.480
130,000 animals every minute
of every day, 24/7, 365.

00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:23.660
That's a lot of animals,
and it's taking a toll.

00:02:23.660 --> 00:02:27.500
Because it's so inefficient to
funnel crops through animals

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:31.070
to get to protein, we lose loads
of resources in the process--

00:02:31.070 --> 00:02:32.810
like all that water.

00:02:32.810 --> 00:02:35.660
The meat, dairy, and egg
industries, all told,

00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:38.360
are so wasteful,
they're so inefficient,

00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:40.610
that they now cause
more greenhouse gas

00:02:40.610 --> 00:02:44.840
emissions than every car,
truck, plane, ship, and train

00:02:44.840 --> 00:02:47.850
in the world combined.

00:02:47.850 --> 00:02:50.840
But the problems aren't just
global, they're local, too.

00:02:50.840 --> 00:02:53.550
I met this woman
recently named Lisa,

00:02:53.550 --> 00:02:55.610
who lives on the eastern
shore of Maryland

00:02:55.610 --> 00:02:57.410
on land that's been
part of her family

00:02:57.410 --> 00:02:59.570
for like four generations.

00:02:59.570 --> 00:03:01.550
Totally normal
neighborhood in most ways.

00:03:01.550 --> 00:03:03.100
Picture any suburban
neighborhood,

00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:05.720
split-level homes,
toys in the front yard,

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:08.030
basketball hoop in the driveway.

00:03:08.030 --> 00:03:09.650
But Lisa and her
husband Joe, they're

00:03:09.650 --> 00:03:11.090
being pushed off their land.

00:03:11.090 --> 00:03:13.423
They're probably going to
have to sell their house soon.

00:03:13.423 --> 00:03:15.500
They're not being pushed
out by crime or drugs

00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:16.910
or high-rise condos.

00:03:16.910 --> 00:03:19.450
They're being pushed
out by chickens.

00:03:19.450 --> 00:03:21.440
See, having moved into
their neighborhood

00:03:21.440 --> 00:03:23.150
are these massive
chicken warehouses

00:03:23.150 --> 00:03:27.620
containing 10,000 birds, 20,000
birds, right in their backyard.

00:03:27.620 --> 00:03:29.570
I visited them last
year, and I was really

00:03:29.570 --> 00:03:31.310
moved to see how
just kind of peppered

00:03:31.310 --> 00:03:32.685
throughout their
neighborhood are

00:03:32.685 --> 00:03:34.760
these massive warehouses now.

00:03:34.760 --> 00:03:36.590
I saw the hoards of
flies in the air.

00:03:36.590 --> 00:03:37.960
I smelled the stench.

00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:40.367
I saw buzzards flying
overhead constantly,

00:03:40.367 --> 00:03:42.950
ready to pick off dead chickens
littering the side of the road

00:03:42.950 --> 00:03:45.380
all up and down
their neighborhood.

00:03:45.380 --> 00:03:47.015
I had to see all
this on one day,

00:03:47.015 --> 00:03:48.671
but Lisa and Joe
and their neighbors,

00:03:48.671 --> 00:03:50.420
they have to live with
it every single day

00:03:50.420 --> 00:03:53.010
right in their backyard.

00:03:53.010 --> 00:03:55.920
So we have to ask ourselves,
does this still make sense?

00:03:55.920 --> 00:03:58.102
We've used animals
as that middleman

00:03:58.102 --> 00:03:59.810
to get to protein for
thousands of years,

00:03:59.810 --> 00:04:01.610
but do we still have to?

00:04:01.610 --> 00:04:04.820
In 2018, if breakfast
sandwiches didn't exist

00:04:04.820 --> 00:04:07.250
and we wanted to build
one from the ground up,

00:04:07.250 --> 00:04:09.080
using what we have
available today,

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:11.630
we wouldn't look towards
chickens to produce the eggs

00:04:11.630 --> 00:04:14.690
and we wouldn't look towards
pigs to produce the sausage.

00:04:14.690 --> 00:04:17.480
In the same way that if the
idea of watching movies at home

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:20.720
was somehow brand new to us in
2018, the thing we wouldn't do

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:23.030
is go out and build
physical video rental stores

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:25.370
to have to drive
to on Friday night.

00:04:25.370 --> 00:04:29.390
We use science and technology to
cut out middlemen all the time.

00:04:29.390 --> 00:04:31.480
And the same is
happening with food.

00:04:31.480 --> 00:04:33.557
And rather than
growing all these crops

00:04:33.557 --> 00:04:35.890
and funneling them through
animals, raising the animals,

00:04:35.890 --> 00:04:37.389
slaughtering them
to get to protein,

00:04:37.389 --> 00:04:41.240
we can just use the protein
that's already found in plants.

00:04:41.240 --> 00:04:43.010
And the food industry
is doing this.

00:04:43.010 --> 00:04:45.410
They're making chicken
without chickens.

00:04:45.410 --> 00:04:46.970
They're making
plant-based burgers

00:04:46.970 --> 00:04:48.890
that have more protein
than beef in them.

00:04:48.890 --> 00:04:52.040
They're making pork without
pigs, and even cheese

00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:54.440
from nuts instead of cows.

00:04:54.440 --> 00:04:57.410
These products are way
more efficient to produce.

00:04:57.410 --> 00:05:01.160
They require less water and
less land and other inputs.

00:05:01.160 --> 00:05:03.170
And they're also better for us.

00:05:03.170 --> 00:05:06.061
Plant-based proteins tend to
have less fat, less saturated

00:05:06.061 --> 00:05:06.560
fat.

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:09.140
They have zero cholesterol,
since cholesterol only

00:05:09.140 --> 00:05:12.290
comes from animal proteins.

00:05:12.290 --> 00:05:13.607
But what if we want real meat?

00:05:13.607 --> 00:05:15.440
I'm not talking about
meat made from plants,

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:20.630
but actual flesh, actual tissue,
real muscle, without animals?

00:05:20.630 --> 00:05:22.340
Impossible, right?

00:05:22.340 --> 00:05:25.190
In 1931, Winston
Churchill was asked

00:05:25.190 --> 00:05:27.980
to predict what the world would
look like in a half a century--

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:29.270
so by the '80s.

00:05:29.270 --> 00:05:32.600
And he predicted that we shall
escape the absurdity of growing

00:05:32.600 --> 00:05:35.480
a whole chicken in order to
eat the breast or the wing

00:05:35.480 --> 00:05:37.070
by growing those
parts separately

00:05:37.070 --> 00:05:38.722
under a suitable medium.

00:05:38.722 --> 00:05:40.430
Well, it didn't happen
by the '80s, which

00:05:40.430 --> 00:05:43.060
is what Churchill predicted,
but it's happening now.

00:05:43.060 --> 00:05:44.440
It's called clean meat.

00:05:44.440 --> 00:05:46.540
And like clean energy,
it's way more resource

00:05:46.540 --> 00:05:48.220
efficient to produce.

00:05:48.220 --> 00:05:51.400
We can now take a biopsy the
size of a poppy seed from just

00:05:51.400 --> 00:05:53.890
a single chicken feather--
just the feather--

00:05:53.890 --> 00:05:55.570
and from that,
grow enough nuggets

00:05:55.570 --> 00:05:59.200
to feed an army or a village.

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:01.510
So these innovations are
shifting our relationship

00:06:01.510 --> 00:06:04.021
with food at the cellular level.

00:06:04.021 --> 00:06:05.770
Because what we eat
is really an extension

00:06:05.770 --> 00:06:07.960
of what it is to
be human, I believe

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:09.850
that fundamentally
changing our relationship

00:06:09.850 --> 00:06:13.150
with food in this way can serve
to elevate our own humanity.

00:06:13.150 --> 00:06:16.870
I think it can lead to a
kinder more compassionate world

00:06:16.870 --> 00:06:19.090
for everybody.

00:06:19.090 --> 00:06:21.520
We humans are an
amazing species.

00:06:21.520 --> 00:06:23.650
We're capable of really
wonderful things.

00:06:23.650 --> 00:06:26.560
We've got a spark of
imagination and creativity

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:29.650
that's unparalleled in the
rest of the animal kingdom.

00:06:29.650 --> 00:06:32.272
We're the only species on the
planet that can see the stars,

00:06:32.272 --> 00:06:33.730
dream about what
might be up there,

00:06:33.730 --> 00:06:36.170
and then actually
go and find out.

00:06:36.170 --> 00:06:38.110
There's so much
about us as a species

00:06:38.110 --> 00:06:41.210
that really is unique to us.

00:06:41.210 --> 00:06:43.720
But at the same time, we
also share so much in common

00:06:43.720 --> 00:06:45.880
with the rest of
the animal kingdom--

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:49.310
joy, play, communication.

00:06:49.310 --> 00:06:51.250
Do you all know
that chickens use

00:06:51.250 --> 00:06:54.350
complex vocalizations to
communicate with one another?

00:06:54.350 --> 00:06:55.334
Just like we do.

00:06:55.334 --> 00:06:57.250
They have different calls
to alert one another

00:06:57.250 --> 00:07:01.300
when a predator is approaching
by land versus by air.

00:07:01.300 --> 00:07:03.670
Fish can learn and use tools.

00:07:03.670 --> 00:07:05.740
Pigs rank higher on
intelligence tests

00:07:05.740 --> 00:07:07.840
than three-year-old humans do.

00:07:07.840 --> 00:07:10.850
And, of course, we all
want to avoid pain.

00:07:10.850 --> 00:07:12.550
We all want to avoid suffering.

00:07:12.550 --> 00:07:16.330
Every animal wants
to avoid fear.

00:07:16.330 --> 00:07:17.740
If through our
diets we can learn

00:07:17.740 --> 00:07:20.170
to really value these
similarities that we share

00:07:20.170 --> 00:07:22.060
with other species
rather than just focusing

00:07:22.060 --> 00:07:25.030
on our differences, I think it
would bring tremendous value

00:07:25.030 --> 00:07:27.030
to how we treat one another.

00:07:27.030 --> 00:07:29.260
So a fish was born with
gills instead of lungs,

00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:32.810
so a chicken was born with
wings instead of arms,

00:07:32.810 --> 00:07:35.170
if we can extend our
circle of compassion

00:07:35.170 --> 00:07:38.650
to those beings even
most unlike ourselves,

00:07:38.650 --> 00:07:40.690
how might we extend it
to our fellow humans?

00:07:40.690 --> 00:07:43.337
To those born black
instead of white or gay

00:07:43.337 --> 00:07:44.170
instead of straight?

00:07:44.170 --> 00:07:47.090
To those born in another
country than we were?

00:07:47.090 --> 00:07:50.230
Can you picture a world
where we take so seriously

00:07:50.230 --> 00:07:52.690
this idea of value
in our similarities

00:07:52.690 --> 00:07:54.850
rather than just always
focusing on our differences

00:07:54.850 --> 00:07:57.595
that it extends even to
the food we choose to eat?

00:07:57.595 --> 00:07:59.470
What about a world where
we're happier, where

00:07:59.470 --> 00:08:00.910
we're plagued less by disease?

00:08:00.910 --> 00:08:02.780
A world where we're healthier?

00:08:02.780 --> 00:08:04.210
A world with a
more stable climate

00:08:04.210 --> 00:08:06.820
where we do more with less?

00:08:06.820 --> 00:08:09.820
My road to picturing this world
came about many years ago.

00:08:09.820 --> 00:08:12.520
When I was about 12,
my sister came home

00:08:12.520 --> 00:08:14.404
from school a vegetarian.

00:08:14.404 --> 00:08:15.820
This was in the
early '90s, if you

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:17.770
couldn't guess by the clothes.

00:08:17.770 --> 00:08:20.470
And I never even heard the word
"vegetarian" before, let alone

00:08:20.470 --> 00:08:21.770
met one.

00:08:21.770 --> 00:08:23.950
So what I do, like any
good little brother,

00:08:23.950 --> 00:08:25.600
I made fun of her.

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:29.580
You can imagine, with that hair,
I was the making fun of her.

00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:31.570
I'd put a piece of steak
on the end of my fork

00:08:31.570 --> 00:08:33.970
and put it in her face
and make a mooing sound.

00:08:33.970 --> 00:08:38.140
My mom, fortunately, was much
more accommodating than I was.

00:08:38.140 --> 00:08:40.757
If she had a pot of beef chili
for the two of us on the stove,

00:08:40.757 --> 00:08:43.090
she'd have a pot of bean chili
next to it for my sister.

00:08:43.090 --> 00:08:45.220
If she was grilling
hamburgers in the backyard,

00:08:45.220 --> 00:08:47.440
she'd have a veggie
burger out there, as well.

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:48.671
And I liked food.

00:08:48.671 --> 00:08:50.170
I wasn't opposed
to trying new food.

00:08:50.170 --> 00:08:53.110
So I started to try some
of these weird, new foods.

00:08:53.110 --> 00:08:54.310
And I liked them.

00:08:54.310 --> 00:08:55.480
I was no vegetarian, though.

00:08:55.480 --> 00:08:58.570
If I had a black bean burger,
I would put bacon on it.

00:08:58.570 --> 00:09:00.850
If I had a bean burrito
one day for lunch,

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:02.600
I'd made sure to have
chicken for dinner,

00:09:02.600 --> 00:09:04.030
just to balance it out.

00:09:04.030 --> 00:09:06.340
Eventually, I did learn
more and more and more

00:09:06.340 --> 00:09:08.530
about the reasons for
my sister's new diet,

00:09:08.530 --> 00:09:10.450
and I also moved
in that direction.

00:09:10.450 --> 00:09:13.100
So if you haven't
guessed by now,

00:09:13.100 --> 00:09:15.100
our breakfast sandwich
that we're going to enjoy

00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:18.350
isn't made from cheese
and sausage and eggs.

00:09:18.350 --> 00:09:20.320
The cheese is made from almonds.

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:24.190
The sausage is made from
[INAUDIBLE] protein.

00:09:24.190 --> 00:09:26.260
The eggs are made
from chickpea flour.

00:09:26.260 --> 00:09:29.080
The whole thing is entirely
plant-based, without animals,

00:09:29.080 --> 00:09:30.220
and it's delicious.

00:09:30.220 --> 00:09:33.670
So that world
where we're kinder,

00:09:33.670 --> 00:09:35.620
where we're more
compassionate, the world

00:09:35.620 --> 00:09:38.830
where our meals are
extensions of our morals,

00:09:38.830 --> 00:09:40.580
that's a better
world for all of us.

00:09:40.580 --> 00:09:42.490
And I know that
all of us have it

00:09:42.490 --> 00:09:45.165
within us to serve as
ambassadors for that world.

00:09:45.165 --> 00:09:46.540
Every time we sit
down to eat, we

00:09:46.540 --> 00:09:49.540
can be a good example for
our friends and neighbors,

00:09:49.540 --> 00:09:52.270
at school, at church,
at work; a good example

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:54.905
for our little brothers
and little sisters.

00:09:54.905 --> 00:09:57.280
And millions of people are
doing it all over the country.

00:09:57.280 --> 00:10:00.010
People are trying
Meatless Monday.

00:10:00.010 --> 00:10:01.700
They're eating smaller
portions in meat.

00:10:01.700 --> 00:10:03.700
They're moving meat from
the center of the plate

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:04.741
to the side of the plate.

00:10:04.741 --> 00:10:07.600
They're doing one or
two veggie meals a day.

00:10:07.600 --> 00:10:11.170
Saving the world really
can be as simple as that.

00:10:11.170 --> 00:10:13.150
And it begins with every bite.

00:10:13.150 --> 00:10:14.720
So thank you so much.

00:10:14.720 --> 00:10:17.440
And I am happy to
field any questions.

00:10:17.440 --> 00:10:19.221
I know Marty's got
a couple that we're

00:10:19.221 --> 00:10:20.470
going to kick things off with.

00:10:20.470 --> 00:10:21.070
SPEAKER 2: Sure thing.

00:10:21.070 --> 00:10:21.945
SPEAKER 1: Thank you.

