00:10:34.940 --> 00:10:37.940
how you got started
in the culinary arts

00:10:37.940 --> 00:10:39.650
and what kind of led
you to this journey

00:10:39.650 --> 00:10:42.217
to decide to publish
a book on the subject

00:10:42.217 --> 00:10:43.550
that you're so passionate about?

00:10:43.550 --> 00:10:44.030
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:10:44.030 --> 00:10:44.990
I always loved cooking.

00:10:44.990 --> 00:10:46.490
I always loved being
in the kitchen.

00:10:46.490 --> 00:10:47.700
It felt comfortable there.

00:10:47.700 --> 00:10:49.486
When I was really
little, I think

00:10:49.486 --> 00:10:51.110
one of my first
projects in the kitchen

00:10:51.110 --> 00:10:53.840
was I would take all the
spices out of our spice cabinet

00:10:53.840 --> 00:10:56.360
and organizing them to combine
all the little half jars

00:10:56.360 --> 00:11:00.110
of cinnamon and little
half containers of pepper.

00:11:00.110 --> 00:11:02.150
When I was probably
about eight, I

00:11:02.150 --> 00:11:04.370
started cooking
really simple meals.

00:11:04.370 --> 00:11:06.840
I would make scrambled
eggs in the microwave,

00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:07.910
which I don't recommend.

00:11:07.910 --> 00:11:08.100
It's about as good--

00:11:08.100 --> 00:11:08.410
SPEAKER 2: [LAUGH]

00:11:08.410 --> 00:11:09.890
SPEAKER 1: --as it sounds
like it's going to be.

00:11:09.890 --> 00:11:11.180
SPEAKER 2: Even with one of
those cool little contraptions

00:11:11.180 --> 00:11:12.600
off of As You Can See on TV?

00:11:12.600 --> 00:11:13.641
SPEAKER 1: Just in a mug.

00:11:13.641 --> 00:11:14.180
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:14.341 --> 00:11:14.840
Yeah.

00:11:14.840 --> 00:11:15.647
Not very good.

00:11:15.647 --> 00:11:16.980
But I just always loved cooking.

00:11:16.980 --> 00:11:19.820
And then, especially when I
became vegetarian and then

00:11:19.820 --> 00:11:22.220
when I became vegan,
I realized that there

00:11:22.220 --> 00:11:24.110
was like this whole
culinary world

00:11:24.110 --> 00:11:25.670
out there that I
had no idea about.

00:11:25.670 --> 00:11:27.530
I'd never tried Thai food.

00:11:27.530 --> 00:11:28.854
I'd never tried Indian food.

00:11:28.854 --> 00:11:30.770
I didn't even know that
these things existed--

00:11:30.770 --> 00:11:33.710
Ethiopian food, tofu, tempeh.

00:11:33.710 --> 00:11:37.020
Just all kinds of new tastes and
textures and flavors that I'd

00:11:37.020 --> 00:11:38.450
never even heard about before.

00:11:38.450 --> 00:11:40.365
And that started me
on my culinary path

00:11:40.365 --> 00:11:41.740
was just realizing
that there was

00:11:41.740 --> 00:11:44.030
a whole world of
textures and flavors

00:11:44.030 --> 00:11:45.495
out there for the taking.

00:11:45.495 --> 00:11:46.370
SPEAKER 2: Fantastic.

00:11:46.370 --> 00:11:49.040
And you mentioned
your being a vegan.

00:11:49.040 --> 00:11:52.520
And from a chef's
perspective, a lot

00:11:52.520 --> 00:11:54.050
of times when we hear vegan--

00:11:54.050 --> 00:11:56.120
for folks that are
non-vegans-- it's

00:11:56.120 --> 00:12:00.710
veganism being the only answer
to dietary problems and issues

00:12:00.710 --> 00:12:01.910
that we may face.

00:12:01.910 --> 00:12:03.530
Your approach is
less about being

00:12:03.530 --> 00:12:06.370
a vegan specifically and more
about a complete plant-based

00:12:06.370 --> 00:12:06.870
approach.

00:12:06.870 --> 00:12:08.369
Can you speak a
little bit about why

00:12:08.369 --> 00:12:11.660
you chose that route
versus the typical approach

00:12:11.660 --> 00:12:13.394
that this veganism is
the only way to go?

00:12:13.394 --> 00:12:14.060
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:12:14.060 --> 00:12:16.226
I think that there
is, literally,

00:12:16.226 --> 00:12:17.600
a seat at the
table for everybody

00:12:17.600 --> 00:12:19.820
when it comes to
plant forward eating,

00:12:19.820 --> 00:12:23.810
when it comes to using our
diets as a tool for good

00:12:23.810 --> 00:12:24.510
in the world.

00:12:24.510 --> 00:12:26.360
Whether you're vegan, whether
you're a vegetarian, doing

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:28.550
Meatless Mondays, whether
you've only ever eaten

00:12:28.550 --> 00:12:31.064
one plant-based meal
in your entire life,

00:12:31.064 --> 00:12:32.480
I just think that
there is a place

00:12:32.480 --> 00:12:34.910
for everybody on the spectrum.

00:12:34.910 --> 00:12:37.730
A lot of people now are
doing Meatless Mondays.

00:12:37.730 --> 00:12:39.230
They're just eating
smaller portions

00:12:39.230 --> 00:12:41.510
of meat, like I mentioned,
or just literally

00:12:41.510 --> 00:12:43.460
moving meat from the
center of the plate

00:12:43.460 --> 00:12:46.040
always to being more
of a luxury item

00:12:46.040 --> 00:12:47.600
or on the side of the plate.

00:12:47.600 --> 00:12:49.440
And I think that's the
way change happens.

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:51.500
It takes everybody.

00:12:51.500 --> 00:12:55.620
Regardless of what diet we might
adhere to or try to adhere too,

00:12:55.620 --> 00:12:58.420
it's like all hands
and forks on deck.

00:12:58.420 --> 00:12:59.360
SPEAKER 2: Absolutely.

00:12:59.360 --> 00:13:03.920
Do you find that that approach
has yielded a better reception

00:13:03.920 --> 00:13:07.700
from folks that maybe
are not vegetarian

00:13:07.700 --> 00:13:11.330
or not vegan at all versus
the traditional approach

00:13:11.330 --> 00:13:13.070
that that's been out
there in years past?

00:13:13.070 --> 00:13:13.460
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:13:13.460 --> 00:13:15.668
There's a study that came
out recently from a company

00:13:15.668 --> 00:13:17.100
called Mintel, a research group.

00:13:17.100 --> 00:13:20.690
And they found that there are
about 22 million Americans who

00:13:20.690 --> 00:13:25.790
consider ourselves vegetarian,
but 113 million who

00:13:25.790 --> 00:13:28.081
say they regularly eat
meat alternatives--

00:13:28.081 --> 00:13:30.080
so, veggie burgers and
other products like that.

00:13:30.080 --> 00:13:33.560
So there are way more people
who are eating vegetarian food

00:13:33.560 --> 00:13:35.690
than actually are vegetarian.

00:13:35.690 --> 00:13:40.970
So without a doubt that's what
most people are doing nowadays.

00:13:40.970 --> 00:13:43.190
SPEAKER 2: I think
as we're starting

00:13:43.190 --> 00:13:46.640
to learn some of the effects
that Matthew pointed out

00:13:46.640 --> 00:13:50.780
in his presentation of
the raising of livestock

00:13:50.780 --> 00:13:53.360
on our environment-- and
it's still a fairly new thing

00:13:53.360 --> 00:13:54.350
that I think we're
starting to wrap

00:13:54.350 --> 00:13:55.880
our heads around a
little bit, and the news

00:13:55.880 --> 00:13:56.755
is getting out there.

00:13:56.755 --> 00:13:58.592
But I think my
question to you is

00:13:58.592 --> 00:14:00.800
given that you've been
passionate about this for such

00:14:00.800 --> 00:14:04.550
a long time, how did you
get into that piece of this

00:14:04.550 --> 00:14:08.150
and connect a vegan or
plant-forward lifestyle

00:14:08.150 --> 00:14:12.110
to the environment at
such an early stage?

00:14:12.110 --> 00:14:14.480
SPEAKER 1: I've always
been passionate, I guess,

00:14:14.480 --> 00:14:16.880
about environmental issues.

00:14:16.880 --> 00:14:20.720
I'm a child of the '80s, when
you couldn't turn on the TV

00:14:20.720 --> 00:14:22.430
without hearing
about global warming.

00:14:22.430 --> 00:14:24.260
Does everybody remember that?

00:14:24.260 --> 00:14:25.311
It was just everywhere.

00:14:25.311 --> 00:14:27.060
Now, we call it climate
change, of course.

00:14:27.060 --> 00:14:29.670
Back in the '80s, everybody was
talking about global warming.

00:14:29.670 --> 00:14:32.360
And so I just started learning
about it from a young age.

00:14:32.360 --> 00:14:37.070
The thing that really made
me move forward with my diet,

00:14:37.070 --> 00:14:39.200
I think, was I mentioned
how my sister came home

00:14:39.200 --> 00:14:41.330
from school a vegetarian
and I made fun of her.

00:14:41.330 --> 00:14:42.630
I didn't really get it.

00:14:42.630 --> 00:14:44.130
But we'd always had
animals at home.

00:14:44.130 --> 00:14:45.070
We always had pets.

00:14:45.070 --> 00:14:46.760
We had cats; we had dogs.

00:14:46.760 --> 00:14:48.074
And I loved them.

00:14:48.074 --> 00:14:49.615
Like most people,
always kind of just

00:14:49.615 --> 00:14:51.080
shared a bond with animals.

00:14:51.080 --> 00:14:55.400
And I guess a few years after
my sister had proclaimed herself

00:14:55.400 --> 00:14:58.880
vegetarian, I
stumbled upon a video

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:01.290
of what happens to animals
in the livestock sector.

00:15:01.290 --> 00:15:02.389
The way that they're--

00:15:02.389 --> 00:15:04.430
without getting too graphic,
the way that they're

00:15:04.430 --> 00:15:07.070
confined in cages and
crates barely larger

00:15:07.070 --> 00:15:09.710
than their own bodies,
the way they're inhumanely

00:15:09.710 --> 00:15:11.510
treated and slaughtered.

00:15:11.510 --> 00:15:15.080
And it just hit me that--

00:15:15.080 --> 00:15:18.500
my dog, Kelsey, at home, a
German shepherd; my cat teaser,

00:15:18.500 --> 00:15:19.610
a black cat--

00:15:19.610 --> 00:15:22.730
if I wouldn't want those
things done to those animals,

00:15:22.730 --> 00:15:24.500
I shouldn't be
paying somebody to do

00:15:24.500 --> 00:15:25.812
those things to other animals.

00:15:25.812 --> 00:15:27.270
And all of a sudden,
I just got it.

00:15:27.270 --> 00:15:29.160
I understood why my sister
had become vegetarian.

00:15:29.160 --> 00:15:31.410
And that was really the thing
that pushed me over the edge.

00:15:31.410 --> 00:15:32.909
After I changed my
diet, that's when

00:15:32.909 --> 00:15:35.100
I started learning
more about the impact

00:15:35.100 --> 00:15:39.180
that my old diet had on the
environment, about water usage

00:15:39.180 --> 00:15:40.682
and land usage
and climate change

00:15:40.682 --> 00:15:42.140
and that connection
to what we eat.

00:15:42.140 --> 00:15:46.130
But for me, it was just wanting
to be kinder to animals.

00:15:46.130 --> 00:15:49.800
SPEAKER 2: In terms of some
of your favorite ingredients,

00:15:49.800 --> 00:15:53.640
what are some things that
you cannot live without,

00:15:53.640 --> 00:15:56.430
whether it's at your home or
things in the book that you

00:15:56.430 --> 00:15:59.070
think are a key thing for
someone to have in their pantry

00:15:59.070 --> 00:16:01.200
as they start this journey?

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:02.040
SPEAKER 1: Nuts.

00:16:02.040 --> 00:16:03.998
Definitely nuts, unless
you have a nut allergy.

00:16:03.998 --> 00:16:04.740
Sorry.

00:16:04.740 --> 00:16:07.220
I don't, so I use a lot of them.

00:16:07.220 --> 00:16:09.500
Nuts are a really amazing food.

00:16:09.500 --> 00:16:11.910
We can do so much with them.

00:16:11.910 --> 00:16:14.370
We can soak cashews,
blend them up

00:16:14.370 --> 00:16:16.080
with just a little
bit of water and salt,

00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:18.270
and make a cheesy sauce.

00:16:18.270 --> 00:16:19.920
If you've ever had
almond milk, that's

00:16:19.920 --> 00:16:22.890
basically what almond milk is--
soaked almonds that have been

00:16:22.890 --> 00:16:24.280
ground up and then strained.

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:26.050
That's essentially almond milk.

00:16:26.050 --> 00:16:31.190
There are just so many
creamy, cheesy, milky sauces

00:16:31.190 --> 00:16:34.120
and other kinds of products
that we can make using nuts.

00:16:34.120 --> 00:16:37.430
There's a whole wide world
out there of nut-based foods.

00:16:37.430 --> 00:16:39.180
Other great ingredients--
I love a product

00:16:39.180 --> 00:16:40.310
called nutritional yeast.

00:16:40.310 --> 00:16:41.870
SPEAKER 2: Mm-hm.

00:16:41.870 --> 00:16:44.930
SPEAKER 1: I'd never heard
of it before I became vegan.

00:16:44.930 --> 00:16:46.500
And I'm so glad
that I know about it

00:16:46.500 --> 00:16:47.940
now because it's incredible.

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:51.120
Whether you're vegan or
not, sprinkle it on popcorn

00:16:51.120 --> 00:16:52.962
and your life will be changed.

00:16:52.962 --> 00:16:54.920
It's kind of got a Parmesan
cheese type flavor.

00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:57.210
It's kind of sharp and tangy.

00:16:57.210 --> 00:16:58.252
Really wonderful product.

00:16:58.252 --> 00:16:59.960
SPEAKER 2: My wife
and I literally put it

00:16:59.960 --> 00:17:01.050
on pretty much everything.

00:17:01.050 --> 00:17:02.280
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:02.280 --> 00:17:04.012
Whole Foods sells it.

00:17:04.012 --> 00:17:05.220
I think Safeway now sells it.

00:17:05.220 --> 00:17:05.720
[INAUDIBLE]

00:17:05.720 --> 00:17:06.390
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:17:06.390 --> 00:17:07.708
Back in the--

00:17:07.708 --> 00:17:10.240
I don't even know if we
could buy it in the '80s,

00:17:10.240 --> 00:17:12.520
but certainly in the
'90s and the early 2000s,

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:14.490
it was like a vegan staple.

00:17:14.490 --> 00:17:17.190
Now, more and more people
are catching on to it

00:17:17.190 --> 00:17:19.470
and just think, wow,
this is a great food.

00:17:19.470 --> 00:17:22.589
SPEAKER 2: And on that
note, with the rise of kind

00:17:22.589 --> 00:17:26.430
of processed plant
proteins, I will say--

00:17:26.430 --> 00:17:28.680
and you eluded to a few of
them in your presentation--

00:17:28.680 --> 00:17:32.200
I think the Impossible
Foods burger up there--

00:17:32.200 --> 00:17:35.430
how do those fit into
your plan and how do those

00:17:35.430 --> 00:17:38.910
fit into your vision
as to how to round out

00:17:38.910 --> 00:17:40.224
a plant-forward diet?

00:17:40.224 --> 00:17:40.890
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:17:40.890 --> 00:17:42.880
I eat processed foods.

00:17:42.880 --> 00:17:44.610
I eat those types of
convenience foods.

00:17:44.610 --> 00:17:48.570
There are all kinds of
plant-based, plant-forward,

00:17:48.570 --> 00:17:51.570
meat-like but meat-free
products of veggie chickens

00:17:51.570 --> 00:17:53.130
and the Impossible
Burgers and Beyond

00:17:53.130 --> 00:17:57.360
Burgers that now they say
even "bleed" like meat does,

00:17:57.360 --> 00:17:58.950
but all from
plant-based ingredients.

00:17:58.950 --> 00:17:59.860
I love that stuff.

00:17:59.860 --> 00:18:00.720
I eat it.

00:18:00.720 --> 00:18:03.270
I would say mostly my
diet, just personally,

00:18:03.270 --> 00:18:07.170
consists more of like whole
plant-based food items.

00:18:07.170 --> 00:18:09.660
I like eating that stuff
on the go if I'm traveling.

00:18:09.660 --> 00:18:11.130
There are a couple of
restaurants in my neighborhood

00:18:11.130 --> 00:18:12.380
that serve that type of stuff.

00:18:12.380 --> 00:18:15.510
I like to go there if I just
want like a juicy burger.

00:18:15.510 --> 00:18:18.280
But, by and large, I just focus
on whole plant-based foods--

00:18:18.280 --> 00:18:23.010
whole grains, legumes,
nuts, beans, tofu, tempeh--

00:18:23.010 --> 00:18:24.590
products like that.

00:18:24.590 --> 00:18:27.525
SPEAKER 2: Do you have a
favorite recipe in the book?

00:18:27.525 --> 00:18:28.775
One that really speaks to you?

00:18:28.775 --> 00:18:30.941
SPEAKER 1: I can't be biased
against my own recipes.

00:18:30.941 --> 00:18:33.480
SPEAKER 2: It's like choosing
a favorite child, I suppose?

00:18:33.480 --> 00:18:33.870
SPEAKER 1: That's right.

00:18:33.870 --> 00:18:34.200
Yeah.

00:18:34.200 --> 00:18:36.285
I tell all the recipes
I love them all equally.

00:18:36.285 --> 00:18:37.035
SPEAKER 2: [LAUGH]

00:18:37.620 --> 00:18:41.441
SPEAKER 1: It's not true,
though, but I do say that.

00:18:41.441 --> 00:18:43.440
Actually, one of my
favorite recipes in the book

00:18:43.440 --> 00:18:44.550
