00:21:33.120 --> 00:21:35.780
if we use them more than we
are now, less, or not at all.

00:21:35.780 --> 00:21:37.600
But I think the one thing that--

00:21:37.600 --> 00:21:38.830
the point that I tried
to make in my book,

00:21:38.830 --> 00:21:41.110
and I think the one thing that
pretty much everybody can agree

00:21:41.110 --> 00:21:42.720
on now, whether
you're slaughtering

00:21:42.720 --> 00:21:44.470
a chicken in your
backyard, whether you're

00:21:44.470 --> 00:21:46.240
eating meat three
times a day, is

00:21:46.240 --> 00:21:48.342
we've got to eat
less of this stuff

00:21:48.342 --> 00:21:50.300
if we want to bring about
a better food supply.

00:21:50.300 --> 00:21:53.320
There's no way that our
planet can sustain--

00:21:53.320 --> 00:21:56.350
just in the US alone-- raising
10 billion land animals--

00:21:56.350 --> 00:21:58.510
that doesn't even include fish--

00:21:58.510 --> 00:22:00.340
raising 10 billion
land animals a year

00:22:00.340 --> 00:22:02.590
under industrial
conditions, locked in cages,

00:22:02.590 --> 00:22:05.287
locked in crates, just
totally decimating the land.

00:22:05.287 --> 00:22:07.120
Because, at the end of
the day, the animal--

00:22:07.120 --> 00:22:11.110
even if it's a heritage bird or
if it's an industrial-produced

00:22:11.110 --> 00:22:12.880
animal--

00:22:12.880 --> 00:22:15.400
the same equation applies
in terms of their conversion

00:22:15.400 --> 00:22:19.540
of plant matter into protein.

00:22:19.540 --> 00:22:24.790
And so regardless of the source,
we have to eat less of them.

00:22:24.790 --> 00:22:27.680
A heritage chicken is
still eating grain,

00:22:27.680 --> 00:22:30.310
for the most part, that may
have been grown on land that was

00:22:30.310 --> 00:22:32.980
once the Amazon rain forest.

00:22:32.980 --> 00:22:36.214
And so, yeah, I think it's
just-- it's all about less.

00:22:36.214 --> 00:22:36.880
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:37.300
